            <div type="article">
                <div type="section" xml:id="EFT-KB-FIVE-POWERS-FIVE-FACULTIES-article-1">
                    <p tid="6">May refer to several sets of “five faculties” or “powers” depending on context. </p>
                    <milestone unit="chunk" xml:id="EFT-KB-FIVE-POWERS-FIVE-FACULTIES-2"/>
                    <label tid="26">The five sense faculties, or the five sensory organs; also called dbang po gzugs can pa lnga: </label>
                    <list type="bullet" rend="numbers">
                        <item>
                            <p tid="8">vision, or the eye (cakṣurindriya, mig gi dbang po) </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="9">hearing, or the ear (śrotrendriya, rna ba’i dbang po) </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="10">smell, or the nose (ghrāṇendriya, sna’i dbang po) </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="11">taste, or the tongue (jihvendriya, lce’i dbang po) </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="12">touch, or the body (kāyendriya, lus kyi dbang po) </p>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                    <milestone unit="chunk" xml:id="EFT-KB-FIVE-POWERS-FIVE-FACULTIES-3"/>
                    <label tid="27">Five “powers” or faculties employed on the bodhisattva path, particularly as applied in the first two stages of the path of application
                        (prayogamārga, sbyor lam); also called rnam byang gi dbang po lnga </label>
                    <list type="bullet" rend="numbers">
                        <item>
                            <p tid="14">the faculty of faith (śraddhendriya, dad pa’i dbang po) </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="15">the faculty of perseverance (vīryendriya, brtson ’grus kyi dbang po) </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="16">the faculty of recollection (smṛtyindriya, dran pa’i dbang po) </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="17">the faculty of meditative stability (samādhyindriya, ting nge ’dzin gyi dbang po) </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="18">the faculty of discriminative awareness (prajñendriya, shes rab kyi dbang po) </p>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                    <p tid="19">(see also “the thirty-seven factors of the path to enlightenment” (saptatriṃśatbodhipakṣīyadharmā, byang chub phyogs kyi chos so bdun) </p>
                    <milestone unit="chunk" xml:id="EFT-KB-FIVE-POWERS-FIVE-FACULTIES-4"/>
                    <label tid="28">In certain Abhidharma contexts (see also tshor ba lnga): </label>
                    <list type="bullet" rend="numbers">
                        <item>
                            <p tid="21">bde ba’i dbang po </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="22">bdug bsngal gyi dbang po </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="23">yid bde ba’i dbang po </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="24">yid mi bde ba’i dbang po </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="25">btang snyoms kyi dbang po </p>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                    <milestone unit="chunk" xml:id="EFT-KB-FIVE-POWERS-FIVE-FACULTIES-5"/>
                    <p tid="29">In some medical texts, the five vital organs (heart, liver, kidneys, lungs, spleen), also called lus kyi don lnga. </p>
                </div>
